x4freetext: The beam polarization was periodically reversed
during the run, at a frequency of 5 Hz, and it was
continuously monitored with a carbon polarimeter. The
average beam polarization was about 85%, and the
typical beam current on target between 8 and 10 nA.
16 Si(Li) detectors, 4 mm thick, cooled to
approximately -20 degr. with a circulating freon
system. The collimator system in front of each detector
consisted of two slits. One, at a distance of 79 mm
from the center of the target, was a 1 mm wide tantalum
slit. The second, at 144 mm from the target, was a
rectangular tantalum collimator 1 mm wide and 8 mm
tall. The resulting angular resolution was about
0.8 degr. The over-all energy resolution, including
the kinematical spread, was between 80 and 100 keV for
all counters.
The 98% pure 18O isotope was contained in a cylindrical
gas cell of 3 cm diam, with entry and exit windows
covered by 2 mg/cm2 thick Havar foils. The target was
run at a pressure of 0.5 atm and the pressure was
continuously monitored with a high precision dial
manometer.
